<number id="3D80E01BFFAEF470BE46E20DFDE6FB74" box="[614,630,1148,1172]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
. Dorsum and sides of head with strong, widely spaced rugae, in side view rugae converging near or slightly anterior to vertex, interrugal spaces smooth and strongly shining. In full-face view, head slightly broader than long, posterior margin flat. Mandible with six teeth on one queen, the other with a seventh tooth that occurred as a denticle between the basal and sub-basal teeth (
<figureCitation id="1373EEB9FFAEF470BFE7E299FBB9FAE0" box="[967,1065,1256,1280]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1972,1995]" captionTargetBox="[426,1161,195,1951]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[426,1162,195,1951]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 9. Photograph of Pogonomyrmex mohavensis Johnson alate queen: (A) frontal view of head, (B) lateral view of body, and (C) dorsal view of body." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/222907/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">
Figure 
<number id="3D80E01BFFAEF470B83AE299FBB9FAE0" box="[1050,1065,1256,1280]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
), dorsal surface coarsely rugose, strongly shining. Eye not large (OI = 
<number id="3D80E01BFFAEF470BE63E37DFD40FAC4" box="[579,720,1292,1316]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" value="21.03" valueMax="21.39" valueMin="20.67">20.67–21.39</number>
), MOD ranging from 
<number id="3D80E01BFFAEF470BFEBE37DFBA9FAC4" box="[971,1081,1292,1316]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" value="0.225" valueMax="0.23" valueMin="0.22">0.22–0.23</number>
x HL. Base of scape noticeably flattened; superior and inferior lobes very well developed, wider than width of scape base.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF7F23CFFAEF470BCE7E324FC8DF989" blockId="19.[151,1437,715,2037]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">Mesosoma as described above, propodeum unarmed; in side view, juncture of dorsum of propodeum and propodeal declivity rounded to subangulate, sides and dorsal surface rugose, shining, posterior surface smooth and strongly shining. Petiolar peduncle long, ventral margin straight. In side view, petiolar node asymmetrical with anterior surface shorter than posterior surface. Apex of node weakly rounded. Postpetiole broader than long. Posterior face of petiole with coarse transverse, oblique, or longitudinal rugae, dorsum of postpetiole with weaker transverse rugae, interrugal spaces weakly to moderately punctate, sub-shining. Gastric tergites weakly coriarious to mostly smooth and shining. Most body surfaces with moderately abundant coarse suberect to erect white setae. Entire body concolorous light to dark ferruginous orange.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF7F23CFFAEF470BCE7E005FE17F96C" blockId="19.[151,1437,715,2037]" box="[199,391,1652,1676]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">
<emphasis id="B93C2E2EFFAEF470BCE7E005FE9BF96C" bold="true" box="[199,267,1652,1676]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">Male.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C352A1B7FFAEF470BCE7E0E9FB6EF814" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BF7F23CFFAEF470BCE7E0E9FB6EF814" blockId="19.[151,1437,715,2037]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">
<emphasis id="B93C2E2EFFAEF470BCE7E0E9FEDBF951" bold="true" box="[199,331,1688,1713]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">Discussion.</emphasis>
The queens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4889BFFFAEF470BDDCE0E8FD0BF950" box="[508,667,1688,1712]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mohavensis">
<emphasis id="B93C2E2EFFAEF470BDDCE0E8FD0BF950" box="[508,667,1688,1712]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">P. mohavensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4889BFFFAEF470BEF4E0E8FCE9F950" authorityName="Johnson, Overson &amp; Moreau" authorityYear="2013" box="[724,889,1688,1712]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoelldobleri">
<emphasis id="B93C2E2EFFAEF470BEF4E0E8FCE9F950" box="[724,889,1688,1712]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">P. hoelldobleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are very similar. The best characters to separate queens of these two species appear to be: (
<number id="3D80E01BFFAEF470BE59E0CDFD15F934" box="[633,645,1724,1748]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" value="1.0">1</number>
) number of teeth (seven in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4889BFFFAEF470BF9EE0CCFBF3F934" authorityName="Johnson, Overson &amp; Moreau" authorityYear="2013" box="[958,1123,1724,1748]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoelldobleri">
<emphasis id="B93C2E2EFFAEF470BF9EE0CCFBF3F934" box="[958,1123,1724,1748]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">P. hoelldobleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, six or with a seventh tooth that occurs as a denticle between the basal and sub-basal teeth in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4889BFFFAEF470BF56E090FB85F918" box="[886,1045,1760,1784]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mohavensis">
<emphasis id="B93C2E2EFFAEF470BF56E090FB85F918" box="[886,1045,1760,1784]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">P. mohavensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), (
<number id="3D80E01BFFAEF470B816E091FBD5F918" box="[1078,1093,1760,1784]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" value="2.0">2</number>
) sculpturing (posterior face of petiole and dorsum of postpetiole weakly to moderately granulate or with weak tranverse rugae in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4889BFFFAEF470B8CFE174FA04F8FC" authorityName="Johnson, Overson &amp; Moreau" authorityYear="2013" box="[1263,1428,1796,1820]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoelldobleri">
<emphasis id="B93C2E2EFFAEF470B8CFE174FA04F8FC" box="[1263,1428,1796,1820]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">P. hoelldobleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; posterior face of petiole with coarse transverse, oblique, or longitudinal rugae, dorsum of postpetiole with weaker transverse rugae in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4889BFFFAEF470BD53E13CFD82F884" box="[371,530,1868,1892]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mohavensis">
<emphasis id="B93C2E2EFFAEF470BD53E13CFD82F884" box="[371,530,1868,1892]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">P. mohavensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and (
<number id="3D80E01BFFAEF470BE42E13DFDE0F884" box="[610,624,1868,1892]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" value="3.0">3</number>
) conformation of the base of the scape (base of scape rounded, superior and inferior lobes poorly developed in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4889BFFFAEF470BE7DE100FC95F868" authorityName="Johnson, Overson &amp; Moreau" authorityYear="2013" box="[605,773,1904,1928]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoelldobleri">
<emphasis id="B93C2E2EFFAEF470BE7DE100FC95F868" box="[605,773,1904,1928]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">P. hoelldobleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; base of scape noticeably flattened, superior and inferior lobes well developed in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4889BFFFAEF470BD8CE1E4FDDBF84C" box="[428,587,1940,1964]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mohavensis">
<emphasis id="B93C2E2EFFAEF470BD8CE1E4FDDBF84C" box="[428,587,1940,1964]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">P. mohavensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The queens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4889BFFFAEF470BF2CE1E4FC3CF84C" box="[780,940,1940,1964]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mohavensis">
<emphasis id="B93C2E2EFFAEF470BF2CE1E4FC3CF84C" box="[780,940,1940,1964]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">P. mohavensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also were significantly larger (HW = 
<quantity id="4CB05FD9FFAEF470B97DE1E5FF6CF830" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.045" metricValueMax="2.08" metricValueMin="2.01" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" unit="mm" value="2.045" valueMax="2.08" valueMin="2.01">2.01– 2.08 mm</quantity>
) than those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4889BFFFAEF470BD85E1C8FDDAF830" authorityName="Johnson, Overson &amp; Moreau" authorityYear="2013" box="[421,586,1976,2000]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoelldobleri">
<emphasis id="B93C2E2EFFAEF470BD85E1C8FDDAF830" box="[421,586,1976,2000]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">P. hoelldobleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(HW = 
<quantity id="4CB05FD9FFAEF470BE88E1C9FCDFF830" box="[680,847,1976,2000]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.615" metricValueMax="1.79" metricValueMin="1.44" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" unit="mm" value="1.615" valueMax="1.79" valueMin="1.44">1.44–1.79 mm</quantity>
). However, these queens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4889BFFFAEF470B8ACE1C8FABBF830" box="[1164,1323,1976,2000]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mohavensis">
<emphasis id="B93C2E2EFFAEF470B8ACE1C8FABBF830" box="[1164,1323,1976,2000]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">P. mohavensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are likely to be significantly larger than those in other parts of their range where the workers are much smaller.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
